    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/09412033978642026623" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Barry</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2015/09/september-6-2/#comment-43813"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-09-07T14:30:13-04:00">Monday, September 7, 2015 at 2:30 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I&#39;ve had the very good fortune to eat meals in both the restaurant and cafe at Chez Panisse. Given the choice, I would almost always choose the cafe (except for landmark meals). Whether as a solo diner or in larger groups, the cafe staff has always welcomed me and provided extraordinary service &#8211; friendly but not cloying, attentive but not intrusive. This service has always seemed an important part of the Chez Panisse approach to food. </p>
<p>Of course, the food in both restaurant and cafe has been definitive. I&#39;ll never forget a side of mac and cheese. I&#39;ll never forget a lemon verbena tea. I could go on but the main point is that the simple delights of Chez Panisse, all performed perfectly, have held a richer and more complete place in memory than the more elaborate service and dishes (even when done perfectly) at other restaurants.</p>
<p>I appreciate reading of your experience, both at Chez Panisse and with its founder. </p>
    </div>

